WEBVTT

00:05.106 --> 00:07.206
Hey, guys.
Dad, you got to tell Mom

00:07.208 --> 00:09.775
we never want to go hiking
with her again.

00:12.179 --> 00:16.115
No, I don't think
I'm gonna do that.

00:16.117 --> 00:18.450
Now that I know
you don't like it,

00:18.452 --> 00:21.120
it could be used
as a form of punishment.

00:21.122 --> 00:23.322
Gonna put that
right in the old dad bank.

00:23.324 --> 00:27.326
It turned into
a four-hour lesson in geology.

00:27.328 --> 00:29.828
I was just looking
for a snake to bite me

00:29.830 --> 00:31.530
so we could be airlifted out.

00:31.532 --> 00:32.631
Yeah.

00:32.633 --> 00:34.299
Turns out every rock
has a story,

00:34.301 --> 00:37.469
and they're all boring.

00:37.471 --> 00:38.537
That's not the case.

00:38.539 --> 00:40.305
What about
Dwayne "The Rock" Johnson?

00:40.307 --> 00:41.974
Okay. Wrestler
turned movie star.

00:41.976 --> 00:43.876
[ Sighs ]

00:43.878 --> 00:46.979
It's inspiring.

00:46.981 --> 00:49.181
You know, ever since
Mom lost her job at the school,

00:49.183 --> 00:51.150
everything
is one big teachable moment.

00:51.152 --> 00:52.818
She's proofreading
my music.

00:52.820 --> 00:55.487
I mean, proper grammar
has no place in songwriting.

00:55.489 --> 00:57.756
If she was Mick Jagger's mom,
we'd all be singing,

00:57.758 --> 01:01.994
"I am unable to receive
any satisfaction."

01:01.996 --> 01:04.329
Man, she never stops,

01:04.331 --> 01:05.831
and I thought
you were the know-it-all.

01:05.833 --> 01:09.168
Yeah. Only about business or
cars or outdoor stuff or life.

01:09.170 --> 01:10.602
Yeah, you got me there.

01:10.604 --> 01:13.005
Listen,
let's cut her a little slack.

01:13.007 --> 01:14.673
She lost her teaching job.

01:14.675 --> 01:16.875
She's got a hole in her life
right now, all right?

01:16.877 --> 01:18.277
Why can't she
just have an affair?

01:18.279 --> 01:20.012
That would take the pressure
off of all of us.

01:23.384 --> 01:25.684
She's going through
a rough time.

01:25.686 --> 01:26.785
We're her family.

01:26.787 --> 01:28.520
It wouldn't hurt
to show a little compassion.

01:28.522 --> 01:29.955
Vanessa:
Oh, good, you're home.

01:29.957 --> 01:32.958
Uh, listen, I found something
fun for us to learn together.

01:32.960 --> 01:34.526
Great.

01:34.528 --> 01:38.697
I signed us up
for ballroom dancing.

01:38.699 --> 01:41.934
Wow!
What a great idea!

01:41.936 --> 01:43.469
Yeah.

01:43.471 --> 01:45.971
Now<i> you</i> get to spend time
with Mom.

01:45.973 --> 01:50.709
I'd love to, but the girls
really want to go hiking again.

01:50.711 --> 01:53.712
-- Captions by VITAC --

01:53.714 --> 01:56.281
♪♪

02:00.654 --> 02:05.891
I can't believe
I got<i> you</i> to take dance lessons.

02:05.893 --> 02:07.893
Is there a particular step
you want to learn?

02:07.895 --> 02:11.296
Yeah, the happy dance
when I know this is over.

02:11.298 --> 02:14.466
So salsa.

02:14.468 --> 02:16.235
You thought about
going back into teaching?

02:16.237 --> 02:18.670
You know what? You're just trying
to get out of the dance lessons.

02:18.672 --> 02:21.907
Uh, yeah.

02:21.909 --> 02:23.742
But I also know
that you miss teaching.

02:23.744 --> 02:25.477
Are you thinking about getting
another job?

02:25.479 --> 02:27.579
Honey, they just laid me off
a month ago.

02:27.581 --> 02:29.581
I mean,
what am I supposed to do,

02:29.583 --> 02:31.583
show up in a wig
and a mustache?

02:31.585 --> 02:32.951
What about
private schools?

02:32.953 --> 02:34.987
I mean, they need help,
and they got money.

02:34.989 --> 02:39.591
When they put an apple
on the desk, it's a MacBook Pro.

02:39.593 --> 02:42.327
I got into teaching to reach
the disadvantaged kids,

02:42.329 --> 02:43.462
not the privileged.

02:43.464 --> 02:46.098
Right. Rich kids need help, too.
No.

02:46.100 --> 02:48.500
You know how much trouble it is
to tie an ascot

02:48.502 --> 02:49.868
while
you're on a polo pony?

02:49.870 --> 02:52.304
"Ridgeway, stop it.

02:52.306 --> 02:56.041
Biffy!
Come on, everybody!"

02:56.043 --> 02:57.776
Rich kids
can afford tutors.

02:57.778 --> 02:59.111
They don't need me.

02:59.113 --> 03:01.547
All right, but when
a public-school job opens up,

03:01.549 --> 03:02.614
you got to be ready.

03:02.616 --> 03:04.483
I think you should stay
in the game.

03:04.485 --> 03:07.319
Yeah, well, I guess
I could think about it.

03:07.321 --> 03:10.622
I mean, I do love teaching
science. [ Chuckles ]

03:10.624 --> 03:12.291
You know,
getting kids to

03:12.293 --> 03:16.728
"zinc" outside
the "bauxite."

03:16.730 --> 03:18.197
[ Laughs ]

03:20.801 --> 03:24.736
This is why science teachers
never opened for Sammy in Vegas.

03:24.738 --> 03:27.739
♪♪

03:27.741 --> 03:30.876
[<i> Zombies groaning</i> ]

03:31.679 --> 03:32.844
[ TV turns off ]

03:32.846 --> 03:35.480
What the -- Why are you
pausing it again?

03:35.482 --> 03:36.715
The zombie was about to
get killed.

03:36.717 --> 03:38.183
Yeah, with a shotgun.

03:38.185 --> 03:39.651
Zombies are attracted
to noise.

03:39.653 --> 03:41.386
He might as well just yell,
"Hey, zombies,

03:41.388 --> 03:42.588
we're in the barn."

03:42.590 --> 03:44.723
Well, that was certainly worth
stopping for.

03:44.725 --> 03:45.657
Can we watch now?

03:45.659 --> 03:47.826
Hold on.
Tell me, Ryan.

03:47.828 --> 03:51.597
The zombie has him cornered.
How is he supposed to kill him?

03:51.599 --> 03:53.999
I'd use a shovel,
which is right there.

03:54.001 --> 03:56.034
A shovel to kill a zombie?

03:56.036 --> 03:58.837
Even if you could
somehow sever the spinal column,

03:58.839 --> 04:01.573
the head
can still bite you.

04:01.575 --> 04:03.542
Kris, can you kill a zombie
with a shovel?

04:03.544 --> 04:06.712
Uh, I'm kind of busy.
Kill him yourself.

04:06.714 --> 04:08.213
We need you to settle
an argument.

04:08.215 --> 04:09.615
Yeah, I'm not
the right person for that

04:09.617 --> 04:11.016
being a grown-up and all.

04:11.018 --> 04:12.084
Hi.
Hi.

04:12.086 --> 04:14.119
You know,
I really wish we could enjoy

04:14.121 --> 04:16.755
some mutilation and bloodshed
like civilized people,

04:16.757 --> 04:19.524
but all you two morons do
is argue.

04:19.526 --> 04:22.561
That's because one of us thinks
he's an expert.

04:22.563 --> 04:24.529
I don't want to say who,
but he has a beard

04:24.531 --> 04:27.399
and his name is Ryan.

04:27.401 --> 04:29.534
Vogelson.

04:29.536 --> 04:32.137
Well, one of us has read
every zombie graphic novel,

04:32.139 --> 04:35.040
seen every movie, TV show,
and even the one zombie musical.

04:35.042 --> 04:37.042
Name it. Too late.
"Thriller."

04:37.044 --> 04:38.377
Okay, you know what?

04:38.379 --> 04:40.879
It's the same thing every week,
so I'm settling this.

04:40.881 --> 04:42.748
Next week we're going to have
a contest.

04:42.750 --> 04:45.384
I'm going to crown one of you
the ultimate zombie authority.

04:45.386 --> 04:46.551
And that would be me.

04:46.553 --> 04:49.888
Nope, that would be me
times infinity.

04:49.890 --> 04:52.457
I'm going to give you the
details of a zombie invasion.

04:52.459 --> 04:54.793
You are each going to have to
tell me how you would survive.

04:54.795 --> 04:56.061
I pick the winner.

04:56.063 --> 04:57.996
He's the ultimate
zombie know-it-all.

04:57.998 --> 05:00.932
We never pause the show again.
Boom.

05:00.934 --> 05:02.734
You're on.
Deal.

05:02.736 --> 05:04.670
All right, now can we please
watch the dead people in peace?

05:04.672 --> 05:06.638
Both: Undead.

05:06.640 --> 05:08.674
I'm getting a shovel.

05:08.676 --> 05:11.810
♪♪

05:14.148 --> 05:15.480
Thanks for coming with me,
sweetie,

05:15.482 --> 05:16.682
but you really
didn't have to.

05:16.684 --> 05:18.583
Have to what?
Support my mother?

05:18.585 --> 05:20.819
Nothing is more important to me
than you...

05:20.821 --> 05:23.922
getting a job.

05:23.924 --> 05:25.624
You know,
I never really saw myself

05:25.626 --> 05:27.092
teaching
at a private school,

05:27.094 --> 05:28.293
but this place is amazing.

05:28.295 --> 05:29.361
I know.

05:29.363 --> 05:30.862
It's like Hogwarts
without the magic

05:30.864 --> 05:32.831
and the gross
British people.

05:32.833 --> 05:35.334
Oh, no, no, no, no.
There's magic here.

05:35.336 --> 05:37.469
The magic of learning.

05:37.471 --> 05:39.404
Abra-ca-science!

05:41.342 --> 05:44.142
Dear God, you need to get back
in a classroom.

05:44.144 --> 05:46.011
Hi. I'm here
for the interview.

05:46.013 --> 05:47.379
Uh, Vanessa Baxter.

05:47.381 --> 05:49.948
Take a seat, and Mr. Slattery
will be right with you.

05:49.950 --> 05:51.116
No hurry.

05:51.118 --> 05:53.385
The students should always have
top priority.

05:53.387 --> 05:56.822
Those women are also here
for the teaching position.

05:56.824 --> 05:59.057
Oh, they're --
they're not students?

05:59.059 --> 06:03.061
Uh, then I will need to see
Mr. Slattery immediately.

06:03.063 --> 06:04.563
[ Chuckles ]

06:04.565 --> 06:07.032
I'm just kidding.

06:07.034 --> 06:08.233
I'm gonna go sit down.

06:10.137 --> 06:12.003
[ Sighs ] Mandy, honey.

06:12.005 --> 06:13.004
Yeah.

06:13.006 --> 06:14.706
These teachers
are all so young.

06:14.708 --> 06:16.708
That's your competition?
Yeah.

06:16.710 --> 06:18.810
Abra-ca-uh-oh.

06:21.315 --> 06:24.883
Mom, what about her?
She's got some miles on her.

06:24.885 --> 06:26.818
Oh, good. Yeah.
I was starting to get worried.

06:26.820 --> 06:28.787
Looking forward to your
retirement party, Elaine.

06:31.592 --> 06:32.858
That's a good thing.

06:32.860 --> 06:35.494
They'll need someone old
to replace Elaine.

06:35.496 --> 06:36.928
Here he comes.

06:36.930 --> 06:38.764
Mom. Mention Twitter.

06:40.934 --> 06:43.335
Hi. It's nice to meet you,
Vanessa.

06:43.337 --> 06:46.238
Uh, I'm sorry.
Uh, I'm -- I'm Vanessa Baxter.

06:46.240 --> 06:48.106
I'm sorry.
Oh, no. No problem.

06:48.108 --> 06:51.843
I realize I'm a little older
than your other applicants,

06:51.845 --> 06:55.580
but I encourage you to "zinc"
outside the "bauxite."

06:55.582 --> 06:57.015
Uh...

06:57.017 --> 06:58.950
Uh [chuckles]
I guess that's why

06:58.952 --> 07:02.187
I never opened for Sammy
in Vegas.

07:02.189 --> 07:03.522
Sammy?

07:03.524 --> 07:05.056
Davis.

07:05.058 --> 07:05.924
Jr.?

07:05.926 --> 07:08.093
Um...

07:08.095 --> 07:09.461
-Twitter?
-No.

07:09.463 --> 07:11.463
♪♪

07:17.938 --> 07:19.704
Hey, kid.
Hey, heads up.

07:19.706 --> 07:21.273
Mom is super sad.

07:21.275 --> 07:24.209
She got passed over again
for another job.

07:24.211 --> 07:26.812
I don't get it.
Who wouldn't want her?

07:26.814 --> 07:29.714
Except us here at home.

07:29.716 --> 07:31.416
Crap.

07:31.418 --> 07:32.751
Who would've thought

07:32.753 --> 07:34.586
it'd be harder to get her
in a good school than you?

07:34.588 --> 07:37.389
I know.

07:37.391 --> 07:40.425
Turns out being smart --
not that important.

07:40.427 --> 07:44.229
What's important is youth.
I was right all along.

07:44.231 --> 07:46.231
I guess you were.

07:46.233 --> 07:49.134
No one's out there searching
for the fountain of age.

07:52.406 --> 07:54.573
Hey, hon.
Are you okay?

07:54.575 --> 07:57.909
Can't compete
with these younger teachers.

07:57.911 --> 08:02.981
You know, one of them actually
called me "ma'am" today.

08:02.983 --> 08:07.118
I almost punched her
in her polite little face.

08:07.120 --> 08:09.921
<i> Almost.</i>

08:09.923 --> 08:11.456
That's why
you're losing these jobs.

08:11.458 --> 08:13.158
No follow-through.

08:14.928 --> 08:17.329
Honey, come on.
You're better than these kids.

08:17.331 --> 08:19.931
No, honey,
the schools don't know that.

08:19.933 --> 08:21.933
They see me walk in the room
and they think,

08:21.935 --> 08:24.102
"Oh, she won't stick around
for 30 years."

08:24.104 --> 08:25.470
You should use me
as a reference.

08:25.472 --> 08:28.173
I'll tell them how difficult
it is to get rid of you.

08:30.978 --> 08:32.210
You know what?

08:32.212 --> 08:33.712
They're always gonna pick
the younger person,

08:33.714 --> 08:34.880
and the sooner I accept that,

08:34.882 --> 08:36.882
the sooner I can stop
humiliating myself.

08:36.884 --> 08:38.850
That's not
the Vanessa I know.

08:38.852 --> 08:41.686
Oh, well, maybe that's because
I've hit rock bottom.

08:43.790 --> 08:46.958
[ Chuckles ]
Rock bottom?

08:46.960 --> 08:49.294
Really?

08:49.296 --> 08:51.530
You let that sit there
and no geology pun?

08:51.532 --> 08:54.065
Oh.
I didn't even see it.

08:54.067 --> 08:55.567
I have lost it.

08:55.569 --> 08:57.536
You haven't.
Baby, come on.

08:57.538 --> 08:58.703
You haven't lost it.

08:58.705 --> 09:00.472
You just got to
take some time off, rest,

09:00.474 --> 09:04.175
recharge your batteries,
and you come out swinging.

09:04.177 --> 09:06.077
No, Mike, I give up.

09:08.148 --> 09:11.016
I am officially retired.

09:11.018 --> 09:13.518
You retire
the same year as Peyton Manning?

09:13.520 --> 09:14.853
That's almost too much.

09:14.855 --> 09:18.023
♪♪

09:18.025 --> 09:22.260
The sun sets
over Denver, Colorado.

09:22.262 --> 09:25.330
The city is swarming
with zombies.

09:25.332 --> 09:30.201
Infections are occurring
at a rate of 100 per hour.

09:30.203 --> 09:32.003
Major complication --

09:32.005 --> 09:33.838
the virus
is being spread by...

09:33.840 --> 09:34.839
Water, wind.

09:34.841 --> 09:36.074
Uber drivers.

09:38.845 --> 09:41.546
...bats.

09:41.548 --> 09:44.049
Which swarm at night,
and it's getting dark.

09:44.051 --> 09:46.585
Wait, and zombification occurs
through a bite?

09:46.587 --> 09:48.219
Stop asking
stupid questions.

09:48.221 --> 09:50.622
It's almost sundown.

09:50.624 --> 09:52.023
To make matters worse,

09:52.025 --> 09:55.060
there is one super zombie
that can turn you with a stare.

09:55.062 --> 09:57.028
You always hear about
the super zombie,

09:57.030 --> 09:58.663
but you never think
it's real.

10:00.634 --> 10:02.534
All communication
is cut off.

10:02.536 --> 10:04.402
All you have is a truck
and fuel -- Kyle, go.

10:04.404 --> 10:06.137
Uh, first stop
is Outdoor Man.

10:06.139 --> 10:08.206
Stock up on weapons, ammo,
and jerky,

10:08.208 --> 10:09.641
but not the pepper teriyaki

10:09.643 --> 10:13.712
'cause they are not kidding
about the pepper.

10:13.714 --> 10:15.280
And then I take the fight
to them --

10:15.282 --> 10:17.115
sounding the horn,
attracting the zombies,

10:17.117 --> 10:19.584
and starting
a full-scale war.

10:19.586 --> 10:21.886
Aggressive.
I like it.

10:21.888 --> 10:23.221
Ryan, proceed.

10:23.223 --> 10:25.724
Oh, well, uh,
first I'd get sunglasses...

10:25.726 --> 10:28.493
It's sundown,
numb-nuts.

10:28.495 --> 10:31.563
...so the super zombie
can't turn me with a stare.

10:31.565 --> 10:34.065
Oh, I had those, too.

10:34.067 --> 10:35.433
Yeah,
I'm sure you would.

10:35.435 --> 10:37.068
Now.

10:37.070 --> 10:39.337
And then I would load Kristin
and Boyd into the truck.

10:39.339 --> 10:41.172
Mm, bonus points
for family protection.

10:41.174 --> 10:43.575
Oh, right, and Mandy's with me.
I just forgot to say that.

10:43.577 --> 10:47.012
Nope. It's too late.
She's on her own.

10:47.014 --> 10:50.682
Although she might be okay
because zombies feast on brains,

10:50.684 --> 10:52.751
and, well,
she has very little to offer.

10:52.753 --> 10:55.987
And next
I would do some shopping.

10:55.989 --> 10:59.758
I'd get seeds, fertilizer,
tools, shiny birthday balloons.

10:59.760 --> 11:01.426
[ Chuckles ]
Birthday balloons?

11:01.428 --> 11:04.696
What else? A piñata?

11:04.698 --> 11:05.797
And then I'd head
to the mountains,

11:05.799 --> 11:06.931
find fertile land

11:06.933 --> 11:09.200
and a fresh water source
with natural barriers.

11:09.202 --> 11:10.869
I'd plant crops,
build a shelter,

11:10.871 --> 11:12.971
and hang the balloons
around the perimeter,

11:12.973 --> 11:18.410
because bats
are repelled by Mylar.

11:21.381 --> 11:22.347
Whoa.

11:22.349 --> 11:24.149
Looks like we have a winner.

11:24.151 --> 11:26.785
[ Grunts ]
I don't want to say who,

11:26.787 --> 11:30.221
but he's got a beard
and his name is Ryan.

11:30.223 --> 11:33.124
Vogelson.

11:33.126 --> 11:35.360
♪♪

11:37.297 --> 11:38.630
[ Door opens ]

11:38.632 --> 11:40.298
Hey, dinner's ready in 10.

11:40.300 --> 11:41.966
Hey, come out here a sec.
[ Door closes ]

11:41.968 --> 11:43.535
You know when I say something
real smart

11:43.537 --> 11:45.003
and you go,
"Mike, you're a genius"?

11:45.005 --> 11:46.638
No.

11:46.640 --> 11:49.741
Well,
that's how it<i> should</i> be.

11:49.743 --> 11:50.742
What do you see here?

11:50.744 --> 11:52.744
A truck.

11:52.746 --> 11:57.549
No, you see
a 1956 Ford truck.

11:57.551 --> 11:58.683
It's a classic.

11:58.685 --> 12:00.685
Mike, you're a genius.
Can I go now?

12:00.687 --> 12:03.655
Just a second. What happens
when we drive around in it?

12:03.657 --> 12:07.058
Um, you make me
take my shoes off.

12:07.060 --> 12:08.827
I know,
but other than that.

12:08.829 --> 12:10.995
I'm not allowed
to wear perfume.

12:10.997 --> 12:12.997
Uh, yeah, besides that.
And?

12:12.999 --> 12:14.666
I can't touch anything.

12:14.668 --> 12:16.334
Right, and I don't like gum
in there, too, but really --

12:16.336 --> 12:17.836
All right.
When we're driving around,

12:17.838 --> 12:20.171
what do other people do
when they see us?

12:20.173 --> 12:23.108
They do this.

12:23.110 --> 12:24.409
You know why they do that? Why?

12:24.411 --> 12:27.512
This truck is older than you,
but it's a classic,

12:27.514 --> 12:29.414
and people realize
it's a classic.

12:29.416 --> 12:31.015
And you're a classic, too.

12:31.017 --> 12:32.417
How flattering.

12:32.419 --> 12:35.620
I'm an old truck.

12:35.622 --> 12:37.188
No, no, no, no.
That's not what I meant.

12:37.190 --> 12:38.256
This is not an old truck.

12:38.258 --> 12:40.792
It was an old truck
until I restored it.

12:40.794 --> 12:42.227
And why did I do that?

12:42.229 --> 12:45.630
Because I know cars,
and I recognized its value.

12:45.632 --> 12:47.866
Well, no one
is recognizing mine, Mike.

12:47.868 --> 12:48.967
But they will.

12:48.969 --> 12:50.301
Somebody who knows something
about teaching

12:50.303 --> 12:51.870
is gonna recognize
your real value.

12:51.872 --> 12:53.204
I know
this is gonna happen.

12:53.206 --> 12:54.239
It really is a beauty --

12:54.241 --> 12:55.640
I'd prefer
you don't touch it.

12:57.210 --> 12:58.543
You know what?

12:58.545 --> 13:01.112
I am a classic, damn it.
That's right.

13:01.114 --> 13:03.114
And the same thing
that happened to this truck

13:03.116 --> 13:03.982
is gonna happen to me.

13:03.984 --> 13:05.216
[ Chuckling ] That's right.

13:05.218 --> 13:07.385
Yeah, I just have to get them
to see my real value.

13:07.387 --> 13:09.420
Bingo. I mean, all
this truck needed

13:09.422 --> 13:11.589
was some bodywork and some new paint...
Yeah, yeah. Uh-huh.

13:11.591 --> 13:13.224
...and that's what I need.

13:13.226 --> 13:14.759
Yeah.

13:14.761 --> 13:16.294
What's that now?
Yeah.

13:16.296 --> 13:18.463
I'm gonna get
plastic surgery.

13:20.233 --> 13:22.167
No, I -- Let's -- Let's reboot
this conversation.

13:22.169 --> 13:23.234
-No.
-Here's -- Look.

13:23.236 --> 13:24.903
Let's use the lawn mower
as an example.

13:24.905 --> 13:27.172
Low, greasy, and dirty. No,
I-I need to be restored.

13:27.174 --> 13:30.241
That is the only way I'm gonna
get to do what I love -- teach.

13:30.243 --> 13:33.411
No, I don't -- Honey -- Honey,
you really are a genius.

13:39.853 --> 13:43.021
Now I won't be able to take<i> her</i>
out in the rain, either.

13:48.795 --> 13:50.094
The frog said, "You get it in,
you pull it out."

13:50.096 --> 13:51.996
[ Laughs ]

13:51.998 --> 13:53.765
Hey. Ed.

13:53.767 --> 13:57.435
Uh, I might need the service
of a good plastic surgeon.

13:57.437 --> 13:59.537
Who's that doctor
that made your third wife

13:59.539 --> 14:01.172
look a lot like
your second one?

14:01.174 --> 14:04.509
You getting a new face,
Baxter?

14:04.511 --> 14:07.846
'Cause I could use a break
from looking at this one.

14:07.848 --> 14:10.114
That's the face
of Outdoor Man.

14:10.116 --> 14:11.816
When people see that face,

14:11.818 --> 14:14.586
they want to buy stuff
to kill something.

14:16.523 --> 14:18.857
Well, thank you both.

14:18.859 --> 14:20.625
It's not for me, actually.

14:20.627 --> 14:22.627
For Vanessa?

14:22.629 --> 14:24.195
Oh, well,
congratulations.

14:26.399 --> 14:28.833
What's she bumping them
up to?

14:28.835 --> 14:30.568
You know,
I'm gonna tell her you said that

14:30.570 --> 14:33.338
next time she goes on and on
about what a classy guy you are.

14:33.340 --> 14:34.873
What's up, Baxter?

14:34.875 --> 14:36.574
Vanessa doesn't need
that kind of thing.

14:36.576 --> 14:38.076
I know.

14:38.078 --> 14:39.143
She's got it in her head

14:39.145 --> 14:40.712
that if she wants to
get back into teaching,

14:40.714 --> 14:44.749
she needs to be restored.

14:44.751 --> 14:47.185
Restored?

14:47.187 --> 14:49.254
Where'd she get
that crazy idea?

14:55.061 --> 14:57.328
Beats me.

14:59.332 --> 15:01.165
Every interview
she's been going on,

15:01.167 --> 15:02.934
she's losing out
to young people.

15:02.936 --> 15:04.435
That's not right.

15:04.437 --> 15:06.838
No, she's got something those
young teachers don't have.

15:06.840 --> 15:10.174
Wisdom.

15:10.176 --> 15:12.677
If the price for that
is a few wrinkles, so be it.

15:12.679 --> 15:15.580
That's why nobody listens
to a grape.

15:17.951 --> 15:22.854
And yet they'll sit at
the feet of a raisin for hours.

15:22.856 --> 15:26.925
Carol always talks about what an
excellent teacher Vanessa was.

15:26.927 --> 15:29.627
She really pushed those kids
and she never gave up on them.

15:29.629 --> 15:30.962
She went in early,
stayed late.

15:30.964 --> 15:33.698
She really loved that job.
Yeah.

15:33.700 --> 15:35.533
And now with class sizes
going up,

15:35.535 --> 15:37.468
a lot of them
are falling through the cracks.

15:37.470 --> 15:40.071
Isn't life strange, huh?
Yeah.

15:40.073 --> 15:43.541
Vanessa wants to teach.
Kids need teaching.

15:43.543 --> 15:47.078
Yet somehow you wind up
paying for a boob job.

15:47.080 --> 15:49.047
Looks like a raisin,

15:49.049 --> 15:50.915
thinks like a grape.

15:50.917 --> 15:52.550
Still want that number?

15:52.552 --> 15:54.085
No,
I don't think I need it.

15:54.087 --> 15:56.788
Chuck, when you're done,
stop by my office.

15:56.790 --> 15:57.789
I got an idea.

15:57.791 --> 16:02.293
♪♪

16:02.295 --> 16:03.661
Hey.
Hey, there.

16:03.663 --> 16:06.831
Uh, we should go.
My -- My consultation's at 3:00.

16:06.833 --> 16:08.800
We can be late.
It's a plastic surgeon.

16:08.802 --> 16:11.803
We'll give him 15 more minutes
of age to work with.

16:11.805 --> 16:14.906
Mike, honey, um,
be honest with me.

16:14.908 --> 16:17.775
Do -- Do you think
this is a good idea?

16:17.777 --> 16:19.010
Hmm.

16:19.012 --> 16:23.848
How can taking a scalpel
to a human face be a bad idea?

16:23.850 --> 16:25.583
Then why haven't you
tried to stop me?

16:25.585 --> 16:27.185
'Cause I thought it'd be fun
in the waiting room,

16:27.187 --> 16:28.586
you and I guessing,
"Hey, is that before,

16:28.588 --> 16:30.655
or, ooh,
is that after?"

16:30.657 --> 16:32.190
I'm serious, come on.

16:32.192 --> 16:34.759
It kills me
that you've been so down lately,

16:34.761 --> 16:36.761
and I would do anything
to make you happy.

16:36.763 --> 16:38.596
And if this is it, I support it.
Okay.

16:38.598 --> 16:42.200
But this is my favorite thing
in the world to look at.

16:42.202 --> 16:44.035
Okay.

16:47.774 --> 16:49.874
I don't know what to do.

16:49.876 --> 16:52.610
That's good,
because I have a secret plan.

16:52.612 --> 16:54.379
What are you
talking about?

16:54.381 --> 16:57.215
Well, I can't tell you because
it's Mike's secret plan.

16:57.217 --> 16:58.316
-Hey, Chuck.
-Hey, Chuck.

16:58.318 --> 16:59.951
-Oh, hey, Vanessa.
-Hi.

16:59.953 --> 17:02.854
I'm so surprised
to see you here.

17:02.856 --> 17:06.190
I did not expect it.

17:06.192 --> 17:07.625
But since you are here,

17:07.627 --> 17:09.694
why don't you come with Mike
and me to the conference room?

17:09.696 --> 17:12.397
This is
a funny coincidence.

17:13.900 --> 17:15.833
[ Forced chuckling ]

17:15.835 --> 17:17.135
Hey.

17:17.137 --> 17:19.237
When you said three years
of community theater,

17:19.239 --> 17:22.407
I had very low expectations.

17:22.409 --> 17:24.542
But wow.

17:32.752 --> 17:36.721
Hey, Mrs. Baxter.
Hey, Jessie, Kevin, David.

17:36.723 --> 17:40.224
Or as I like to call it,
Mike's secret plan.

17:40.226 --> 17:41.893
Well, Carol helped.

17:41.895 --> 17:43.261
She's the one
that called the kids.

17:43.263 --> 17:44.562
And I'm the one
that called Carol,

17:44.564 --> 17:46.464
but, you know, let's just
call it Mike's secret plan.

17:48.334 --> 17:50.501
We didn't know you started
tutoring, Mrs. B.

17:50.503 --> 17:51.436
What?

17:51.438 --> 17:54.072
No, I -- Uh, yeah, yeah.

17:54.074 --> 17:56.240
A lot of people are --
are just finding out about that.

17:56.242 --> 17:57.408
Just say you'll do it.

17:57.410 --> 17:59.243
You got three great people
counting on it.

17:59.245 --> 18:01.579
Me, Mandy, and Eve.

18:01.581 --> 18:04.582
And the conference room could be
a great temporary classroom.

18:04.584 --> 18:06.217
Yeah, they teach a lot of stuff
in here.

18:06.219 --> 18:08.853
Wilderness survival,
backpacking skills, first aid.

18:08.855 --> 18:11.022
You can add
useless science crap.

18:11.024 --> 18:13.024
Ah! He's joking.
It's not useless.

18:13.026 --> 18:14.692
Yeah, but it's confusing.

18:14.694 --> 18:16.427
Well, what, uh -- what
are you having trouble with?

18:16.429 --> 18:19.363
They give us these worksheets,
but nobody explains them to us.

18:19.365 --> 18:22.233
Oh, okay, okay.
This is about light refraction.

18:22.235 --> 18:23.634
Remember when we talked about

18:23.636 --> 18:25.536
colors having
different wavelengths?

18:25.538 --> 18:27.705
She talked about this stuff
at dinner,

18:27.707 --> 18:29.540
so I'm actually
following this.

18:29.542 --> 18:30.608
I remember.

18:30.610 --> 18:33.311
You told us
that's why sunsets are red.

18:33.313 --> 18:35.780
Oh, because red
has the longest wavelength.

18:35.782 --> 18:37.215
Exactly.

18:37.217 --> 18:39.050
See, you guys know
more of this than you think.

18:39.052 --> 18:41.652
And that is something
to<i> refract</i> on.

18:44.324 --> 18:45.623
I'm back!

18:47.894 --> 18:51.562
So, who can tell me
the colors of the spectrum.

18:51.564 --> 18:52.730
ROY G. BIV!

18:54.634 --> 18:57.168
I'm sorry. Sorry.
No. That's okay.

18:57.170 --> 19:00.104
She has a way
of pulling you in.

19:00.106 --> 19:02.440
Honey. Honey.
Look at the time.

19:02.442 --> 19:03.808
Isn't there something
you need to do?

19:03.810 --> 19:07.512
Um, yeah, I'm --
I'm doing it.

19:11.484 --> 19:12.700
Thank you.

19:12.701 --> 19:13.917
Congratulations, Baxter.
You really pulled this off.

19:13.920 --> 19:16.187
Well, I got to be
totally honest with you.

19:16.189 --> 19:17.488
[ Sighs ]

19:17.490 --> 19:19.590
I couldn't have done this
without, uh, your help.

19:19.592 --> 19:23.794
I mean, your backup and support
meant the world to me.

19:23.796 --> 19:26.330
Wow. Thanks, man.

19:26.332 --> 19:29.000
[ Chuckling ]
Now<i> that</i> was acting.

19:31.604 --> 19:34.372
♪♪

19:40.847 --> 19:43.047
Kyle, hey, uh,
the grill is swamped.

19:43.049 --> 19:45.116
Can you help me out
for about a half an hour?

19:45.118 --> 19:47.051
Maybe you should ask Ryan
to do it

19:47.053 --> 19:49.220
in case zombies attack
the restaurant.

19:49.222 --> 19:51.789
I hate that I know
what you're talking about.

19:51.791 --> 19:54.025
He even made himself
a trophy.

19:54.027 --> 19:56.961
He deserves it.
He's a genius.

19:56.963 --> 19:59.297
Planting crops,
fighting bats with balloons.

19:59.299 --> 20:02.667
He saved his family, and I left
Mandy out there on her own.

20:02.669 --> 20:04.735
So you can't help me
because in a made-up game

20:04.737 --> 20:07.738
your wife was eaten
by imaginary zombies?

20:07.740 --> 20:11.342
Hey. I don't want
everybody to know.

20:11.344 --> 20:14.712
I realize that there's
no such thing as zombies.

20:14.714 --> 20:16.180
Yet.

20:16.182 --> 20:19.016
But there are scary things
in the real world.

20:19.018 --> 20:21.319
Will I be able to protect Mandy
from those?

20:21.321 --> 20:24.889
Kyle, do you know what Mandy
has always been afraid of?

20:24.891 --> 20:29.260
Uneven eyebrows?
She mentions that a lot.

20:29.262 --> 20:31.829
Her biggest fear was always
that she wasn't gonna find

20:31.831 --> 20:35.199
the right guy
to share her life with.

20:35.201 --> 20:37.335
So sad.

20:37.337 --> 20:38.703
I know she will.

20:38.705 --> 20:41.906
No, it -- it's you, Kyle.
You're that guy.

20:41.908 --> 20:43.574
Do -- Do you know
how many nights

20:43.576 --> 20:45.676
I spent in Mandy's bedroom
after a bad date

20:45.678 --> 20:47.778
trying to convince her
that all guys weren't awful?

20:47.780 --> 20:50.414
I don't know. Four?

20:50.416 --> 20:52.083
Sure, yeah.

20:52.085 --> 20:53.451
And then one night,

20:53.453 --> 20:56.787
she told me that she found the
guy that made all the dozens...

20:56.789 --> 21:01.459
I mean<i> four</i> guys before him
not matter.

21:01.461 --> 21:03.728
She said that?

21:03.730 --> 21:05.096
Yeah. See?

21:05.098 --> 21:07.064
You already saved her.

21:07.066 --> 21:10.034
And you will every day
for the rest of your life.

21:10.036 --> 21:11.402
Huh.

21:11.404 --> 21:15.106
And I didn't even need
any stupid balloons.

21:15.108 --> 21:17.141
Hey, tell Ryan
to enjoy that trophy,

21:17.143 --> 21:18.909
because it's gonna be mine
someday.

21:18.911 --> 21:22.647
It's a G.I. Joe missing both
arms glued to a piece of wood.

21:24.384 --> 21:26.717
Is there anything
he can't do?

21:26.719 --> 21:28.552
♪♪
